      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Branch Ergonomic Chair</strong> is the best ergonomic chair you can buy for under $400. Its adjustable lumbar support, breathable mesh back, and 7-year warranty put it ahead of every budget competitor and within striking distance of chairs costing three to four times as much. If you sit 6 or more hours a day and cannot justify a $1,395 Herman Miller Aeron, this is the chair to buy.
      </div>

      <p>The ergonomic chair market splits into three tiers that barely overlap. At the bottom, sub-$200 chairs look the part but lack the adjustability and durability that define real ergonomics. At the top, $1,000+ chairs from Herman Miller and Steelcase are genuinely better built and warrantied for 12 years, but most home office workers cannot justify the spend. The middle tier — roughly $300 to $500 — is where the value lives, and the Branch Ergonomic Chair is the chair that defines it.</p>

      <p>We sat in the Branch chair for 90 days straight, working 8-hour days at a standing desk we alternated between sitting and standing. We tested lumbar support by sitting for two-hour stretches without shifting, measured seat pressure with a pressure pad, tracked breathability in an 80-degree room, and disassembled the armrests once to inspect the mechanisms. We also had three testers of different heights (5'4", 5'11", and 6'2") use the chair for full weeks each to see how it adapted.</p>

      <p>This is our deep-dive review. The Branch is also our top pick in the <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">best ergonomic chair under $500 roundup</a>, so if you want the short version, that page has it. Below we get into the specifics that matter once you have decided you are buying a mid-tier chair.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</h2>
      <div class="pros-cons">
        <div class="pros">
          <h3>Pros</h3>
