            <li>Adjustable lumbar support — height and depth, rare under $400</li>
            <li>Breathable mesh back stays cool through 8-hour sessions</li>
            <li>Seat depth adjustment (slide) fits a wider range of body types</li>
            <li>4D armrests adjust in height, width, depth, and pivot</li>
            <li>7-year warranty — longest in this price tier</li>
            <li>Synchro tilt mechanism keeps feet flat when reclined</li>
            <li>Clean, modern aesthetic that fits a home office</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="cons">
          <h3>Cons</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Seat cushion flattens after 8 hours — firm foam would help</li>
            <li>Headrest is a $49 add-on, not included</li>
            <li>Max user height of about 6'2" — tall users need more</li>
            <li>Recline tension is stiff even at the lowest setting</li>
            <li>Castors are basic — hard on carpet after months</li>
            <li>No fabric color options beyond black and gray</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This — and Who Shouldn't</h2>
      <div class="audience">
        <div class="for">
          <h3>Great for</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Remote workers who sit 6+ hours per day</li>
            <li>Buyers who want real lumbar support without spending $1,000+</li>
            <li>People between 5'4" and 6'2" — the adjustment range fits well</li>
            <li>Anyone with a hot home office — the mesh back breathes</li>
            <li>Buyers who want a 7-year warranty at a mid-tier price</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="not-for">
          <h3>Skip it if</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You sit fewer than 4 hours a day — a budget chair is fine</li>
            <li>You are over 6'2" — the seat and backrest are too short</li>
            <li>You want a headrest included as standard</li>
            <li>Your budget can stretch to $1,400 for an Aeron or Leap V2</li>
            <li>You need premium upholstery or color options</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Lumbar Support: The Deciding Feature</h3>
      <p>Lumbar support is the single most important feature on an ergonomic chair, and it is exactly where budget chairs fail. A chair without adjustable lumbar support forces your lower back into a C-curve, which fatigues the muscles that should be holding your spine neutral. After a few weeks of daily use, that fatigue becomes lower-back pain. The Branch chair solves this properly.</p>

      <p>The lumbar support adjusts in both height (4 inches of travel) and depth (about 1.5 inches of travel). That dual adjustment matters more than it sounds. Different body types need the support at different heights — a 5'4" person needs it lower than a 6'2" person — and different preferences need different depth. We set the lumbar to sit just below our testers' L4 vertebrae and adjusted the depth until the pad pressed gently against the curve of the lower back without pushing. After two hours of sitting, none of our testers reported the lower-back fatigue that budget chairs produce.</p>

      <p>For comparison, the budget Hbada chair (around $130) has fixed lumbar support that sits at one height and one depth. If that height happens to match your spine, the chair is fine. If it does not — and for most people it does not — the support either presses into your kidneys or sits uselessly below your back. The Branch's adjustability solves this completely, and it is the single biggest reason to spend $215 more than the Hbada.</p>

      <h3>The Mesh Back: Breathable and Supportive</h3>
      <p>The backrest is a tensioned mesh mounted on a flexible frame. This is the design Herman Miller pioneered with the Aeron, and it works by distributing your weight across the mesh rather than concentrating it on a single foam pad. The result is a backrest that both supports and breathes.</p>

      <p>We tested breathability by sitting in the chair for 8 hours in an 80-degree room with no fan. The mesh back stayed cool throughout — no sweat accumulation, no heat buildup. The seat, which is upholstered fabric over foam rather than mesh, trapped more heat. After about 5 hours our testers reported the seat feeling warm, which is the one real comfort limitation of the chair. If you run hot, consider pairing the chair with a cooling seat cushion or taking standing breaks every 90 minutes.</p>

      <p>The mesh tension held up over our 90-day test. We measured the backrest deflection at the start and end of the test (pressing a 20-lb weight into the center of the mesh and measuring how far it bowed), and the deflection increased by less than 2 percent. Branch uses a woven elastomeric mesh that should hold its tension for years, unlike the cheap elastic mesh on sub-$150 chairs, which sags visibly within months.</p>

      <h3>The Seat: Comfortable, With One Limitation</h3>
      <p>The seat is high-density foam upholstered in a breathable fabric. It is comfortable for the first 5 to 6 hours of a workday, but it compresses noticeably after that — our testers reported feeling the hard pan beneath the foam by hour 7. This is the one area where the Branch chair shows its price. The Aeron and Leap V2 use higher-density foam (or, in the Aeron's case, a tensioned mesh seat) that holds up for 10+ hours without flattening.</p>

      <p>The seat depth is adjustable, sliding forward about 2 inches. That adjustment is genuinely useful if you are short (a shorter seat depth prevents the front edge from pressing into the back of your knees) or tall (a deeper seat supports more of your thigh). The seat slides on smooth rails and locks firmly in place. The front edge has a waterfall curve that reduces pressure on the thighs, and our pressure-pad test showed even pressure distribution across the seat with no hotspots at the front edge.</p>

      <p>If you regularly sit for 8+ hours, the seat is the one reason to consider upgrading to a premium chair. For 6-hour days, the Branch is comfortable throughout. Add a <a href="/reviews/best-foot-rest-desk/">foot rest</a> to take pressure off your thighs and the chair handles long sessions better.</p>

      <h3>The Armrests: 4D and Genuinely Useful</h3>
      <p>The armrests are 4D-adjustable, meaning they move in height, width (in and out), depth (forward and back), and pivot (angle). Each adjustment has a positive lock — the armrest clicks into place and does not slip under pressure. The pads are polyurethane, which is firmer than gel but softer than hard plastic. They survived our 90-day test without visible wear.</p>

      <p>4D armrests matter most for people who type with their elbows on the desk. The ability to drop the armrests below desk height means you can pull the chair all the way in, and the ability to slide them back means they do not bump the desk when you stand up. Budget chairs with fixed or height-only armrests force you to either hover your elbows or rest them at the wrong height, both of which cause shoulder tension over time.</p>

      <p>The one criticism: the armrests are slightly wobbly even when locked. Applying lateral pressure (say, leaning sideways to reach something) produces about 3mm of play. The Aeron's armrests are rock-solid by comparison. This does not affect daily typing, but it is noticeable if you lean on the armrests for support.</p>

      <h3>The Tilt Mechanism: Syncro Tilt Done Right</h3>
      <p>The Branch chair uses a synchro-tilt mechanism, which means the backrest reclines at a faster rate than the seat tilts (typically 2:1). This is the correct mechanism for an ergonomic chair because it keeps your feet flat on the floor when you recline, rather than lifting them off the ground the way a single-tilt chair does.</p>

      <p>The recline has three lockable positions — upright, slightly reclined, and fully reclined — plus a free-float mode for active sitting. The tension is adjustable via a knob under the seat, but even at the lowest tension setting the recline is stiff. Our lightest tester (120 lbs) struggled to recline fully without pushing off the desk. If you are under 150 pounds, the recline will feel restrictive. Heavier testers found it about right.</p>

      <p>The free-float mode is genuinely useful. It lets the chair move with you as you shift weight, which encourages micro-movements that reduce fatigue. We used it for the first week and then mostly forgot about it — but it is there when you want it.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Warranty</h3>
      <p>The chair feels solid for the price. The base is die-cast aluminum (not plastic, as on many budget chairs), the gas cylinder is class-4 rated (the standard for office chairs), and the castors are rated for carpet and hard floors. The frame has no creaks or rattles after our 90-day test, and the upholstery shows no visible wear.</p>

      <p>The 7-year warranty is the longest in this price tier. Branch covers the frame, mechanism, and upholstery for the full period; the gas cylinder is covered for 5 years. For comparison, the Hbada budget chair offers a 1-year warranty, and the SIHIO M18 offers 3 years. The warranty is a real indicator of expected lifespan — Branch is betting the chair will last 7 years of daily use, and based on the build quality we observed, we believe it.</p>

      <p>One honest note on the castors: they are basic nylon castors that work fine on hard floors but struggle on medium-pile carpet. After 90 days, rolling the chair across carpet required noticeable effort. If your office is carpeted, budget $30 for a set of rollerblade-style castors or a chair mat.</p>

      <h3>Assembly: 20 Minutes, One Person</h3>
      <p>Assembly is genuinely a one-person job. The chair ships in one box weighing about 45 lbs. You attach the backrest to the seat, then the seat to the base, then the armrests. The instructions are clear, every bolt is bagged and labeled, and the included Allen key is the right size. Total assembly time was 22 minutes from box to seated.</p>

      <p>This is meaningfully easier than the Aeron, which arrives mostly assembled but requires two people to attach the backrest due to its weight. It is also easier than the budget Hbada, which has fiddly armrest installation that took us 35 minutes.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested five chairs in the Branch's price neighborhood. Here is how the top three plus the premium benchmark stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Chair</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Lumbar Adjust</th>
            <th>Backrest</th>
            <th>Comfort (1-10)</th>
            <th>Warranty</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Branch Ergonomic Chair</strong></td>
            <td>$345</td>
            <td>Height + depth</td>
            <td>Mesh</td>
            <td>8</td>
            <td>7 years</td>
          </tr>
