      </table>

      <p>The SIHIO M18 is the Branch's closest competitor. It costs $66 less, has a similar mesh back, and offers height-adjustable lumbar support. Where it loses ground is depth adjustment (the lumbar cannot be tuned for how hard it presses), the warranty (3 years versus 7), and the seat foam (which flattened faster in our testing). If $66 is a meaningful difference to you, the SIHIO is a solid choice — see our <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-budget/">budget ergonomic chair roundup</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The Hbada is the budget pick. At $130 it is less than half the price of the Branch, but it gives up adjustable lumbar (fixed only), 4D armrests (height only), seat depth adjustment, and 6 years of warranty. For sitting under 4 hours a day, it is fine. For full-time work, the Branch is worth the extra $215.</p>

      <p>The Herman Miller Aeron is the premium benchmark and the chair every ergonomic chair is compared against. It is meaningfully better on every metric — better mesh, better lumbar, better tilt, better build, and a 12-year warranty. But it costs $1,395, which is four times the Branch's price. For most home office workers, the Branch delivers 80 percent of the Aeron experience for a quarter of the cost. Read our <a href="/reviews/herman-miller-aeron-review/">Herman Miller Aeron review</a> to decide if the premium is worth it for you.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Branch Ergonomic Chair if you sit 6 or more hours per day and your budget is in the $300 to $500 range. It is the best chair in that tier, and the 7-year warranty means it will outlast two or three budget chairs. If you sit fewer than 4 hours a day, save the money and buy a $130 Hbada — the Branch's advantages only pay off over long sessions.</p>

      <p>Add the headrest if you recline while reading, taking calls, or thinking. The $49 add-on is height-adjustable and attaches with two bolts. If you only sit upright to type, skip it — the headrest is useless in an upright posture and just adds visual clutter.</p>

      <p>Pick the gray fabric over the black if your office gets warm. The gray reflects more light and feels slightly cooler in direct sun. The black shows less dirt but absorbs heat in a sunny room.</p>

      <p>Replace the castors if your office is carpeted. The included nylon castors are fine on hard floors but struggle on medium-pile carpet. A set of rollerblade-style polyurethane castors costs about $30 on Amazon and makes the chair roll noticeably easier. If your office is hard floor, the stock castors are fine.</p>

      <p>Complete your ergonomic setup. A good chair solves posture, but your desk and monitor still need attention. Pair the chair with a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-converter/">standing desk converter</a> if you want to add sit-stand without replacing your desk, and add a foot rest to take pressure off your thighs during long sessions. If you already have a standing desk, the Branch pairs perfectly with a mid-tier standing desk like the Branch Standing Desk or the FlexiSpot E7.</p>

      <p>If $345 is genuinely out of reach, do not stretch. The <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">best ergonomic chair under $500 guide</a> covers chairs from $130 up, and the Hbada at $130 handles 4-hour days fine. Save the upgrade budget for a standing desk converter or a monitor riser — those two upgrades change how your body feels more than swapping a $130 chair for a $345 one.</p>

